Thread on DMX and his spiritual journey as portrayed in his discography. His dealing with demonic entities, rise to fame, and eventual conversion to Christianity. We start with the track "Damien" from his album "It's Dark and Hell is Hot" youtube.com/watch?v=uFBfvm_S‚Ä¶

The song starts with DMX mourning his bad luck and wondering where his guardian angel is, until he hears a voice that introduces itself as "Damien". Damien promises DMX that he will make him the most successful rapper who has ever lived.

Of course, Damien is nothing but a devil.

In verse 2, Damien proves himself as a "cool" guardian "angel" and tells X that he can do whatever he wishes to.

He specifically encourages him to start abusing substances and be promiscuous.

DMX's success increases. Damien promises more, and X starts considering him a friend.

The track ends with Damien telling X to sacrifice an old friend of his. DMX tries to protest but Damien threatens him and forces him to go along with the murder.

The finishing sentence "I see now ain't nothin' but trouble ahead" is the moment X realizes the mistake he has done.

We jump to the second piece of the story. "The Omen".

The saga continues, with Damien revealing he is actively protecting X and helping him during shootouts. But, in return, he continues demanding blood.

Of course, his promises of riches and fame keep increasing.

Even though DMX is trying to break the "relationship" off, after a "coincidental" incident involving his loved ones, he once again finds himself in need of Damien's protection to avenge their deaths.

He knows that this time he will be forced to "pay" even more than beforehand.

As I realized I forgot to link the song, here it is: youtube.com/watch?v=kqWvSYBJ‚Ä¶ The story culminates with DMX confronting Damien and the demon telling him that he now owns his soul and there is nothing that X can do about it. There is no way to escape or defeat the devil.

The track ends with DMX understanding the true state of the situation, that he found himself in, and praying to God for help.

He knew that only He could save him from the devil and protect his soul from damnation.

Now we get to the most interesting part:

The final battle between X and the devil.

After showing off his powers, Damien directly threatens DMX's wife and children.

Note: In the hook X reveals that he could feel Damien "fucking with him" everywhere, assumedly like a poltergeist

DMX is saddened over how he even managed to begin trusting the devil in the first place, and understands that he could have achieved all of his victories with God's help instead, without being forced to murder and blackening his soul in the process.

Damien threatens DMX again and proceeds to mock him newfound Christianity by calling him "Light Man".

X, now wiser than before, rebukes the demon by calling himself a sinner (Dark Man), showing humility and understanding the sins he has committed in the past.

After some final arguing, Damien claiming that he technically gave X what he promised ("But what did it cost me?"), DMX finally rebukes the devil and prays to Christ for help.

Damien understand that he is unable to win against a man of Christ and finally leaves X's life forever.

The powers that be do not enjoy a man of the Lord's music being popular, so, of course, he is mostly erased from today's cultural consciousness.

His story is even more complicated, with being forced and refusing to put satanic messages in his songs, drug problems et cetera etc.

But, it is the story of a man who fell, who managed to seek redemption, and who found it in our Lord.

He might have lost most of his riches, but he did not lose his soul and he left us some truly, truly good rap music that we can listen to even today
